import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.regex.Matcher;
import java.util.regex.Pattern;

public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    String inputJavadoc = "/**
     * Sends a message over the connection.
     * @param x must be positive
     */
     Input Parameters:
    [{"type": {
      "qualified_name": "int",
      "name": "int",
      "is_array": false
    },
    "name": "x"}]
    Input Return Type:
    null
    String javadocWithMethods = "/**
 * Removes the specified edge from the graph. Removes the specified edge
 * from this graph if it is present. More formally, removes an edge <code>
 * e2</code> such that <code>e2.equals(e)</code>, if the graph contains such
 * edge. Returns <tt>true</tt> if the graph contained the specified edge.
 * (The graph will not contain the specified edge once the call returns).
 *
 * <p>If the specified edge is <code>null</code> returns <code>
 * false</code>.</p>
 *
 * @param e edge to be removed from this graph, if present.
 *
 * @return <code>true</code> if and only if the graph contained the
 * specified edge.
 */
";
    String[] lines = javadocWithMethods.split("\n");
    List<String> parameterList = new ArrayList<>();
    boolean nullCheck = false;
    
    for (String line : lines) {
        Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile("(@param|@return|@throws)\\s*([^\\s]+)", Pattern.CASE_INSENSITIVE);
        Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(line);

        if (matcher.find()) {
            String tag = matcher.group(1);
            String parameterName = matcher.group(2).trim();

            if (tag.equals("null")) {
                nullCheck = true;
            }
            else {
                parameterList.add(getJsonElement(parameterName, tag));
            }

        } else if (line.contains("<code>")) {

          Pattern pattern1 = Pattern.compile("<code>(.*?)</code>");
          Matcher matcher1 = pattern1.matcher(line);
          String parameterContent = matcher1.group(1).trim();

          parameterList.add(getJsonElement(parameterName, "content", parameterContent));
        }
    }

    if (!parameterList.isEmpty()) {
      System.out.println("{");
      for (String json : parameterList) {
        System.out.print(json + ",");
      }
      System.out.println("}");
    }
  }

  private static String getJsonElement(String name, Object type, String content) {
    List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
    if (content != null) {
      list.add(content);
    } else {
      list.add(name);
    }
    
    return "{\"name\":\"" + name + "\",\"description\":\"" 
           + type + "\",\"assertion\":\"" + name + " must be "
           + (type.equals("null") ? "" : "not ") + (content != null ? content : "") + "\"}";
  }

}
```

This code does the following:
1. It splits the input string into lines.
2. For each line, it checks if there is a parameter tag using `@param`.
3. If it finds a `@param` tag, it extracts the name of the parameter and adds a JSON element to the list containing this information. If the content of the parameter is specified, it also includes this in the JSON element.
4. It then checks if there are any other tags (like `@return`) on the same line. If there isn't, it checks for an opening `<code>` tag and adds a JSON element to the list containing this information.
5. Finally, it prints out all of the JSON elements as one big JSON object.

The regular expression used is `(@param|@return|@throws)\\s*([^\\s]+)`, which matches both `@param` tags and some other tags that are not necessary for this task (e.g., `@return`). 

It also handles the case where a parameter's content is specified, as well as the case where the type of the tag is "null", in which case it needs to include a JSON element with an assertion that checks if the parameter is equal to null.
